<h2 id="represent-data-honestly">Represent data honestly</h2>
<p>Charts must represent data truthfully and support informed decisions, not visual emphasis.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Do not manipulate axis scales to exaggerate differences.</li>
  <li>Start bar charts at zero unless there is a documented reason not to.</li>
  <li>Clearly label units, timeframes and scope of the data.</li>
  <li>Avoid 3D styling or visual effects that can distort perception.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Each chart should include</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Clear title</li>
  <li>Axis labels with units</li>
  <li>Legend or direct labels</li>
  <li>Source where relevant</li>
  <li>Last updated date where relevant</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="keep-only-what-matters">Keep only what matters</h2>
<p>Only include data that supports the primary message or decision. Clarity should take priority over density.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Limit the number of data series.</li>
  <li>Avoid clutter or unnecessary visual elements.</li>
  <li>Use annotations to highlight the key insight.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Dashboards</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Place key metrics first.</li>
  <li>Group related charts.</li>
  <li>Avoid horizontal scrolling for primary information.</li>
  <li>If metadata applies to all charts, include it at the container level.</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="chart-anatomy">Chart anatomy</h2>
<p>Every chart must include the core elements required for clarity and accurate interpretation.</p>

<div class="nsw-grid nsw-m-top-sm">
  <div class="nsw-col nsw-col-lg-12">
    <div class="nsw-docs__chart-anatomy">
